  "chapter": {
    "number": 14,
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "Job Laments the Finality of Death"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 1,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "“Man, who is born of woman,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "is short of days and full of trouble.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 2,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Like a flower, he comes forth, then withers away;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "like a fleeting shadow, he does not endure.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 3,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Do You open Your eyes to one like this?",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "Will You bring him into judgment before You?",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 4,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Who can bring out clean from unclean?",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "No one!",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 5,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Since his days are determined",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and the number of his months is with You,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "and since You have set limits",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "that he cannot exceed,",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 6,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "look away from him and let him rest,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "so he can enjoy his day as a hired hand.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 7,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "For there is hope for a tree:",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "If it is cut down, it will sprout again,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "and its tender shoots will not fail.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 8,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If its roots grow old in the ground",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and its stump dies in the soil,",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 9,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "at the scent of water it will bud",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and put forth twigs like a sapling.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 10,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "But a man dies and is laid low;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "he breathes his last, and where is he?",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 11,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "As water disappears from the sea",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and a river becomes parched and dry,",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 12,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "so a man lies down",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and does not rise.",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "Until the heavens are no more,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "he will not be awakened or roused from sleep.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 13,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If only You would hide me in Sheol",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and conceal me until Your anger has passed!",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "If only You would appoint a time for me",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and then remember me!",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 14,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "When a man dies, will he live again?",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "All the days of my hard service I will wait,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "until my renewal",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "noteId": 3169
          },
          {
            "text": "comes.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 15,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "You will call, and I will answer;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "You will desire the work of Your hands.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 16,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "For then You would count my steps,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "but would not keep track of my sin.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 17,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "My transgression would be sealed in a bag,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and You would cover over my iniquity.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 18,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "But as a mountain erodes and crumbles",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and a rock is dislodged from its place,",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 19,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "as water wears away the stones",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and torrents wash away the soil,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "so You destroy a man’s hope.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 20,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "You forever overpower him, and he passes on;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "You change his countenance and send him away.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 21,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If his sons receive honor, he does not know it;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "if they are brought low, he is unaware.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 22,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "He feels only the pain of his own body",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and mourns only for himself.”",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "footnotes": [
      {
        "noteId": 3169,
        "caller": "+",
        "text": "Or my change or my relief",
